{{Infobox book | name = Philip Dru: Administrator: A Story of Tomorrow, 1920-1935 | title_orig = | translator = | image = Philip Dru title page.png | caption = Title page, 1912 | author = [[Edward M. House|Edward Mandell House]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = United States | language = English | series = | genre = [[Political novel]] | publisher = B. W. Huebsch | release_date = 1912 | media_type = | pages = 312 | oclc = 1533564 | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''Philip Dru: Administrator: A Story of Tomorrow, 1920-1935''''' is a futuristic [[political novel]] published anonymously in 1912 by author [[Edward M. House|Edward Mandell House]], an American diplomat, politician, and presidential foreign policy advisor. According to historians, House highly prized his work and gave a copy of ''Dru'' to his closest political ally, [[Woodrow Wilson]], to read while on a trip to Bermuda.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=g1IgBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA74 Colonel House: A Biography of Woodrow Wilson's Silent Partner]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=4jcL20ZS_KUC&pg=PA53 Woodrow Wilson's Right Hand: The Life of Colonel Edward M. House]</ref><ref>See also: Link, ''The Papers of Woodrow Wilson'' - Volume 25</ref> [[File:The Forum (1886) (14595037579).jpg|thumb|''Senator [[John Sherman|Sherman]] Discovers the Basis of Political Morality'', cartoon published in ''The Forum'' (1910)]] ==Book reviews== Historian [[Paul Johnson (writer)|Paul Johnson]] wrote: "Oddly enough, in 1911 he [House] had published a political novel, ''Philip Dru: Administrator'', in which a benevolent dictator imposed a corporate income tax, abolished the protective tariff, and broke up the 'credit trust'—a remarkable adumbration of [[Woodrow Wilson|[Woodrow] Wilson]] and his first term."<ref>{{cite book | last = Johnson | first = Paul |authorlink = Paul Johnson (writer) | title = A History of the American People | publisher = HarperPerennial | location = New York | year = 1999 | pages = 635–636| isbn = 0060930349 }}</ref>
Billie Jensen, a historian from the [[University of Kansas]] noted that "''Philip Dru was obviously an expression both of House's ambition and his political dreams and it was an expression of the ideas of the man who had an impressive amount of influence on Woodrow Wilson. Seldom have the elements of a utopia been implemented so soon as the reforms of Philip Dru were; seldom has a utopian reformer been as influential as House was. For these reasons, Philip Dru is a significant political document.''<ref name=Jensen>[https://libprdojsap.lib.ku.edu/amerstud/article/view/2434 Philip Dru, The Blueprint of a Presidential Adviser]</ref>
In a book review for [[The New York Times]], [[Walter Lippmann]] wrote of the novel and its anonymous author that "''if the author is really a man of affairs, this is an extraordinarily interesting book''".<ref>[*[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9A07E5DB1E3AE633A2575BC0A9649D946396D6CF AMERICA'S FUTURE; Pictured in a Decidedly Quaint Modern Novel], [[Walter Lippmann]], December 8, 1912]</ref>
==Synopsis== Set in 1920-1935,<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=oOEfAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA206 English Mechanics and the World of Science, Volume 92]</ref> House's hero leads the [[Democracy|democratic]] [[western United States]] in a [[Second American Civil War|civil war]] against the [[Plutocracy|plutocratic]] [[Eastern United States|East]]. After becoming the acclaimed leader of the country, he steps down having restored justice and democracy. House outlined many additional political beliefs such as:<ref name=reedy>[https://books.google.com/books?id=fCg-AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA239 What Colonel House Thinks] Book review by [[William Marion Reedy]], ''Reedy's Mirror, April 6th, 1917</ref>
* Federal Incorporation Act, with government and labor representation on the board of every corporation<ref name=reedy /><ref>Chapter XXXII</ref> * Public service corporations must share their net earnings with government<ref name=reedy /><ref>Chapter XXXII</ref> * Government ownership of all telegraphs<ref name=reedy /><ref>Chapter XXXIII</ref> * Government ownership of all telephones<ref name=reedy /><ref>Chapter XXXIII</ref> * Government representation in railroad management<ref name=reedy /><ref>Chapter XXXIII</ref> * Single term presidency<ref name=reedy /><ref>Chapter XLI</ref> * Old age pension law reform<ref name=reedy /><ref>Chapter XXXIX</ref> * Workmen's insurance law<ref name=reedy /><ref>Chapter XXXIX</ref> * Co-operative marketing and land banks<ref name=reedy /><ref>Chapter XXXIX</ref> * Free employment bureaus<ref name=reedy /><ref>Chapter XXXIX</ref> * 8 hour work day, six days a week<ref name=reedy /><ref>Chapter XXXIX</ref> * Labor not to be a commodity<ref name=reedy /><ref>Chapter XXXIX</ref> * Government arbitration of industrial disputes<ref name=reedy /><ref>Chapter XXXIX</ref> * Government ownership of all healthcare<ref name=reedy /><ref>Chapter XXXIX</ref>
===Cast of Characters=== The book has several characters: Philip Dru is the main protagonist of the story. Other characters include Gloria Strawn and her brother Jack Strawn. There is also a character named John Thor and a Senator Selwyn.
